==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang}} {{term|dom|dōm|[[judgement]]|lang=ang}}, cognate with {{etyl|non|-}} {{term|dómr|lang=non}}, Swedish, Danish, and Norwegian "dom"

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/duːm/}}, {{SAMPA|/du:m/}}
* {{audio|en-us-doom.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|uːm}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|-}}

# {{countable|historical}} A law.
#* {{quote-book|author=Beatrice Adelaide Lees|title=Alfred the Great: the truth teller, maker of England, 848-899|page=211|year=1915|passage="What ye will not that other men should do unto you, that do ye not unto other men." "From this one '''doom'''," comments Alfred, "a man may bethink him how he should judge every one rightly: he needs no other '''doom'''book."}}
# {{countable|historical}} A [[judgment]] or [[decision]]
#*{{quote-book|title=[[w:Ancient law|Ancient Law]]|page=22|author=[[w:Henry James Sumner Maine|Henry Sumner Maine]]|year=1861|passage=Kings are spoken of as if they had a store of "Themistes" ready to hand for use; but it must be distinctly understood that they are not laws, but judgments, or, to take the exact Teutonic equivalent, "'''dooms'''."}}
#* {{quote-book|author=Beatrice Adelaide Lees|title=Alfred the Great: the truth teller, maker of England, 848-899|page=208|year=1915|passage=when Alfred in turn set himself to the task of stating and interpreting the law of his kingdom, there were already precedents for him to follow, in the written "'''dooms'''" (domas) of his predecessors, — themselves but a small portion of the still unwritten custom}}
# {{countable|historical}} A [[sentence]] or [[penalty]] for an illegality or type of illegality.
#*{{quote-book|title=An institute of the law of Scotland|page=989|author=John Erskine|co-authors=Sir George Mackenzie, James Ivory|year=1828|passage=Appeals were by our ancient law styled falsing of '''dooms'''. They were to be entered mmediately after '''doom''' or sentence was pronounced, }}
# [[death|Death]]; an adverse or terrible [[fate]], [[end]].
#: ''They met an untimely '''doom''' when the mine shaft caved in.''
#*{{quote-book|year=2009|title=Tangled lies|author=Anne Kristin Stuart|passage=The engines were rumbling, missing every now and then, and Rachel leaned back in her seat, prepared to meet her '''doom''' somewhere over the Pacific. At least there was a priest at hand -- maybe she could entice him to hear a final confession.}}
# [[destiny|Destiny]], especially adverse.
#*{{quote-journal|year=2007|volume=92|issue=4|page=495|title=Fustian Days: Book One: Sonic Goddam Boom|author=Billy Lee Brammer|journal=Southwest Review|passage="When should I expect him?" Roy said, resigned to his '''doom'''.}}
#*{{quote-journal|year=2009|date=December 11|volume=59|issue=8|page=4|title=Robin Hood|author=Karen Gormandy|passage="After he takes the throne, you will be arrested." / "You lie like your master, Carfax. Your '''doom''' is sealed."}}
# An impending severe problem or danger that seems inevitable.
#*{{quote-news|year=2009|date=April 27|section=Sports|page=7C|title=After Lions^ gamble, lots of big men tapped|author=Nate Davis|work=USA Today|passage=Chung was the first of its four picks in Round 2. His arrival might spell '''doom''' for Rodney Harrison.}}
# {{rfv-sense|can "doom" be a feeling?}} A feeling of [[danger]], impending danger, darkness or despair.
#*{{quote-journal|year=2004|volume=89|issue=4|page=479|title=The Turpentine Still|author=Arthur Miller|journal=Southwest Review|passage=unlike Vincent, he wasn't quite taken in by the outbreak of hopefulness on all sides. After all, nothing about the tanks or the process had been resolved; an air of '''doom''' still hung undisturbed over the project.}}
#*{{quote-book|year=2006|title=Once upon a wedding night|author=Sophie Jordan|passage=She halted her pacing steps as the ugly significance of Nicholas Caulfield's pending arrival washed over her. Ruin. Destitution. '''Doom''' settled like a heavy stone in her chest.}}
#*{{quote-journal|year=2007|date=February|volume=71|issue=773|page=45|title=Tapestries in Oil|author=Bob Bahr|journal=American Artist|passage=Such paintings are inherently moody, and Elliott likes that-even as he carefully avoids dictating a specific mood. "Yesterday I painted the last light of the day-the trees looked pink, and the mountain's shadow was coming over them. It created a feeling of nostalgia... or impending '''doom'''... or still, quiet, peacefulness. It depends on the viewer's feelings about the scene, not just mine."}}
#*{{quote-journal|year=2009|date=March|volume=122|issue=3|page=15|title=Forget the rules and make the leap|author=Deanna Roy|journal=Writer|passage=Then the smiling narrator filled me with '''doom''': I was expected to pull my own rip cord. I nearly fainted.}}
# {{context|sometimes capitalized}} The [[Last Judgment]]; ''or'', an artistic representation of it.

